DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines philosophical debates about how technology shapes
human agency, cognition, and autonomy. The extended mind thesis (Clark
& Chalmers 1998) provides the foundational framework, arguing that
cognitive processes can extend beyond the brain into external tools and
artifacts. This raises questions about whether technological
augmentation diminishes or extends human capacities. Recent work
examines cognitive offloading—the delegation of cognitive tasks to
external devices—and its implications for intellectual virtue,
autonomy, and moral agency. A key debate concerns whether offloading
undermines cognitive skills and autonomy or merely reallocates mental
resources to more valuable tasks. Another strand examines how smart
technologies challenge traditional transparency ideals in tool use, and
how moral technologies might offload not just cognitive but also moral
tasks. The domain connects extended mind theory to practical questions
about digital assistants, smartphones, and AI-mediated decision-making.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is critical for distinguishing DIY from tool-assisted
action. If extended mind theory is correct, using tools doesn't
outsource tasks to something external—it extends the self. This
challenges the intuition that tool use differs fundamentally from human
delegation. The cognitive offloading literature addresses whether there
are morally relevant differences between using technology versus relying
on other people, particularly regarding autonomy and skill development.
Understanding how technology shapes agency clarifies what is lost or
gained when we delegate tasks to machines rather than doing them
ourselves.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Most work focuses on cognitive and epistemic dimensions of offloading;
less attention to affective or embodied dimensions. Limited engagement
with how extended mind theory applies to collaborative tasks or
distributed agency. Few papers directly address the moral distinction
between tool use and interpersonal delegation. INCOMPLETE entries
(lacking abstracts): nagelReiner2018skillful (Frontiers in Psychology),
schultz2025natural (Synthese 2025), choi2021internet (unpublished
manuscript), chemero2009radical (book). These entries remain in the
bibliography for reference but are excluded from synthesis.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Emphasize the debate between extended mind proponents and critics who
see offloading as diminishing agency. Distinguish cognitive offloading
(memory, calculation) from moral offloading (decision-making, judgment).
Consider how transparency and skillful use affect whether technology
extends or replaces the self.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Extended mind optimists (8 papers): Technology extends rather than replaces cognition
- Offloading skeptics (5 papers): Cognitive delegation threatens autonomy and skill
- Virtue epistemology critics (3 papers): Offloading undermines intellectual virtues
- Ethical technology designers (2 papers): Skillful use determines moral status
====================================================================
